# State-by-State Lease Compliance Guide

## Security Deposit Laws by State (2026)

### Maximum Deposit Amounts

**No State Limit:**
- Arizona, Colorado, Delaware, Idaho, Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Louisiana, Missouri, New Mexico, Ohio, Oklahoma, Pennsylvania, South Carolina, Texas, Utah, West Virginia, Wisconsin, Wyoming

**1 Month's Rent:**
- California (as of 2024, AB 12)
- Kansas, Kentucky, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, North Carolina, Oregon, Vermont, Virginia

**1.5 Months' Rent:**
- Arkansas, Tennessee

**2 Months' Rent:**
- Alaska, Connecticut, District of Columbia, Maryland, Minnesota, New Jersey, New York, Rhode Island, Washington

**2-3 Months' Rent (varies):**
- Hawaii, Michigan, Mississippi, Montana, Nebraska, North Dakota, South Dakota

**3 Months' Rent:**
- Alabama, Florida, Georgia, Maine, Nevada

### Deposit Return Timelines

**14 Days or Less:**
- Arizona (14), Hawaii (14), Louisiana (14), Massachusetts (30), Mississippi (45), Missouri (30), Nevada (30), North Carolina (30), Oregon (30), Tennessee (30), Vermont (14), Wyoming (30)

**21 Days:**
- California (21), New Jersey (30)

**30 Days:**
- Alaska, Arkansas, Connecticut, Delaware, Florida, Georgia, Idaho, Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kansas, Kentucky, Maine, Maryland, Michigan, Minnesota, Montana, Nebraska, New Hampshire, New Mexico, New York, North Dakota, Ohio, Oklahoma, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, South Carolina, South Dakota, Texas, Utah, Virginia, Washington, West Virginia, Wisconsin

**45-60 Days:**
- Alabama (60), District of Columbia (45)

### Interest on Deposits Required

**States Requiring Interest:**
- Connecticut: Greater of 1.5% or average rate
- Florida: If held 1+ years with 5+ units
- Illinois: If held 6+ months
- Iowa: 5% simple annual
- Maryland: 3% simple annual
- Massachusetts: 5% annual or actual interest
- Minnesota: 1% simple annual
- New Hampshire: Actual interest earned
- New Jersey: ~3% (state-set rate)
- New Mexico: On deposits over $5,000
- New York: Actual interest earned
- North Dakota: Actual interest earned
- Pennsylvania: 0% first year, 1% after
- Virginia: Actual interest earned

## Rent Increase Notice Requirements

### By State

**30 Days' Notice:**
- Most states for month-to-month tenancies
- Annual leases: typically only at renewal

**60 Days' Notice:**
- California (for increases >10%)
- District of Columbia
- Oregon (for increases >10%)
- Nevada (some cases)

**90 Days' Notice:**
- Oregon (for increases >10%)
- Some cities with rent control

### Rent Control States/Cities

**States with Rent Control:**
- California (AB 1482): 5% + CPI, max 10% annually
- Oregon: 7% + CPI annually
- New York: Varies by building age and type

**Major Cities with Rent Control:**
- San Francisco, CA
- Los Angeles, CA
- Oakland, CA
- Berkeley, CA
- New York City, NY
- Washington, DC
- Portland, OR

## Required Disclosures by State

### Lead-Based Paint (Federal)
- **Required for:** Buildings built before 1978
- **All states:** Must provide EPA pamphlet and disclosure form
- **Penalty:** Up to $19,507+ per violation

### State-Specific Disclosures

**California:**
- Lead paint (pre-1978)
- Mold
- Pest control history
- Bedbug history
- Smoke/CO detectors
- Asbestos (if known)
- Methamphetamine contamination
- Registered sex offenders database
- Military ordnance location
- Death in unit (past 3 years)

**Texas:**
- Lead paint (pre-1978)
- Smoking policy
- Security devices
- Previous flooding
- Property tax info
- Ownership information

**Florida:**
- Lead paint (pre-1978)
- Radon gas
- Fire sprinkler system
- Termite/pest damage

**New York:**
- Lead paint (pre-1978)
- Bedbug history (past year)
- Window guards (if children under 10)
- Rent stabilization status
- Owner/manager contact info

**Illinois:**
- Lead paint (pre-1978)
- Radon
- Smoke detectors
- Carbon monoxide detectors
- Chicago: Additional city requirements

## Late Fee Restrictions

### Maximum Late Fees by State

**Percentage-Based Caps:**
- California: Reasonable amount (typically 5-10% of rent)
- Texas: Reasonable amount, courts use 5-10% guideline
- Illinois: Reasonable amount
- New Jersey: Up to 5% after 5-day grace period

**Fixed Amount Caps:**
- Oregon: $20 first late fee, then 6% of monthly rent
- Maine: 4% of monthly rent
- Delaware: 5% of monthly rent
- Arkansas: $25 or 10% of rent

**Grace Period Requirements:**
- Many states require 3-5 day grace period
- Some states require written notice before charging

**No State Limits:**
- Several states have no specific caps but require "reasonableness"

## Eviction Notice Requirements

### Notice Periods for Non-Payment

**3 Days:**
- Arizona, California, Florida, Indiana, Louisiana, Nevada, New Mexico, Ohio, Oklahoma, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington

**5 Days:**
- Minnesota, New Jersey, New York, Oregon, Pennsylvania

**7 Days:**
- Illinois, Maine, North Carolina, Tennessee, Wisconsin

**10 Days:**
- Connecticut, Michigan, Montana

**14 Days:**
- Massachusetts, New Hampshire

**30 Days:**
- Delaware, Virginia

### Notice for Lease Violations

Typically 30 days in most states, with opportunity to cure

### Notice to Vacate (Month-to-Month)

**30 Days:**
- Most states

**60 Days:**
- California (tenant occupancy >1 year)
- Oregon (some cases)

## Habitability Standards

### What Landlords Must Provide (Most States)

**Basic Requirements:**
- Running water (hot and cold)
- Heat in winter
- Electricity
- Working plumbing
- Secure locks
- Weather protection (roof, walls, windows)
- Sanitary conditions
- Smoke detectors
- Carbon monoxide detectors (in many states)

**Pest Control:**
- Landlord responsibility in most states
- Tenant may be responsible if they caused infestation

**Common Area Maintenance:**
- Landlord typically responsible
- Includes hallways, stairs, exterior

## Tenant Rights by State

### Right to Repair & Deduct

**States Allowing:**
- California: Up to 1 month's rent, after notice
- Arizona: After 5-10 days notice
- Massachusetts: After 14 days notice
- Montana: After 14 days notice
- Nebraska: After 14 days notice

**Requirements:**
- Must give proper notice to landlord first
- Issue must affect habitability
- Amount limits vary by state
- Proper documentation required

### Right to Withhold Rent

**States Allowing (with restrictions):**
- California, Massachusetts, New York, Pennsylvania
- Must follow specific procedures
- Issue must severely affect habitability
- Risk of eviction if done improperly

**Not Recommended Without Legal Advice**

## Entry & Privacy Laws

### Notice Requirements

**24 Hours:**
- California, Connecticut, Hawaii, Kentucky, Maine, Massachusetts, Oregon, Rhode Island, Vermont, Virginia, Washington

**48 Hours:**
- Illinois, Indiana, Kansas, Nevada, New Jersey, North Dakota, Ohio, Tennessee, Wisconsin

**Reasonable Notice:**
- Most other states (typically interpreted as 24 hours)

### Permitted Reasons for Entry

**Generally Allowed:**
- Emergency situations (no notice required)
- Repairs and maintenance
- Showing to prospective tenants/buyers
- Inspection
- Court order

**Restrictions:**
- Must be during reasonable hours (typically 8am-8pm)
- Cannot be used to harass tenant
- Tenant can deny entry if improper notice

## Pet Policies by State

### Pet Deposits & Fees

**Included in Deposit Limit:**
- California: Pet deposit counts toward total
- Connecticut: Pet deposit counts toward total

**Separate Pet Deposits Allowed:**
- Most states allow separate pet deposits
- No refundable vs. non-refundable varies

**Pet Rent:**
- Allowed in most states as monthly fee
- Not refundable like deposits
- Check local ordinances

### Emotional Support Animals

**Federal Law (FHA):**
- Cannot charge pet deposit for ESA
- Cannot charge pet rent for ESA
- Must allow ESA even with "no pets" policy
- Can request documentation

**Service Animals:**
- Cannot charge any fees
- Must allow regardless of policy
- Protected under ADA

## Subletting & Assignment

### States Allowing With Landlord Approval

**Landlord Consent Required:**
- Most states require written landlord consent
- Landlord cannot unreasonably withhold consent in some states

**States Where Tenant Has More Rights:**
- New York: Landlord cannot unreasonably deny
- California: Landlord cannot unreasonably deny

**Original Tenant Liability:**
- In most states, original tenant remains liable
- Landlord can pursue both original and new tenant

